1; in 1988, and he won a National award for the best supporting role in the movie &#8220;Parinda&#8221; in 1989. Nana Patekar&nbsp;is not only an actor, but he is also a writer, a screenwriter, a filmmaker, and a philanthropist. While perfecting his role in Prahaar,&nbsp;Nana Patekar&nbsp;had gone through rigorous army training for three years, for which he was given the honorary title of &#8220;Captain&#8221; in the 1990s. He has worked in many great films such as Krantiveer, Ab Tak Chhapan, Taxi No 9 2 11, Yeshwant, etc., and has successfully entranced the audience in every walk of his career. The actor mainly worked in Hindi and Marathi films.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\nNana Patekar,a true philanthropist-&nbsp;\n\nEven though&nbsp;Nana Patekar&nbsp;is an amazing actor and a great filmmaker, he never made a show of his generosity and philanthropy, keeping his personal life and kind deeds to himself.&nbsp;Nana Patekar&nbsp;had stepped himself up for the farmers of Maharashtra when they were suffering in unimaginable ways. During the Vidharba drought in 2015, Nana Patekar&nbsp;had hugely supported the farmers in Maharashtra. He has generously donated to the families of farmers who had committed suicide and gave a cheque of INR 15,000 to almost 62 families in Maharashtra. Nana Patekar&nbsp;has personally visited 112 families in Latur during the period of drought to inspect their conditions and extended a helping hand to them.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\nThe Naam Foundation-&nbsp;\n\nNana Patekar, along with Makarand Anaspune, created the Naam Foundation in September 2015. It was founded considering the negligence towards the devastating drought situations in Maharashtra and the increase in the number of farmer suicides due to the drought. The constant water crisis in those areas led to the rapid degeneration of the villages in Maharashtra. The villagers and the farmers were not getting safe drinking water, let alone the water to cultivate.&nbsp;\nAnd, the climatic conditions of those regions were also not in favour of the farmers. Being a true philanthropist and humanitarian,&nbsp;Nana Patekar&nbsp;founded the Naam Foundation as a response to the problems of the farmers. The Naam Foundation seeks to educate the farmers, reviving the canals and abandoned water projects in that area, and restoring the groundwater. The major aim of the Naam Foundation is to fill up the dried lakes and rivers and provide safe and clean drinking water to the people of Maharashtra. As per his efforts, many of the above prospects have successfully been completed.&nbsp;\nThe Naam Foundation has already managed to collect INR 22 lakhs for the farmers\u2019 welfare from many people. Nana Patekar himself has donated almost 90% of his earnings to charity till now. The Naam Foundation can connect the people to the areas as far as Nagpur, Latur, Hingoli, Parbhani, Nanded, Aurangabad, etc. And has evolved from a movement to an organization facilitating developments in the villages of Maharashtra.&nbsp;\n\nThe houses in which Nana Patekar lives and the lifestyle he leads-&nbsp;\n\nNana Patekar&nbsp;was born and brought up in&nbsp;Murud,&nbsp;Maharashtra and his father passed away at the age of 28 years. Even though he reportedly has assets of INR 40 crores, he lives a very simple life. The lifestyle he leads is a reflection of his way of living. Currently,&nbsp;Nana Patekar\u2019s house&nbsp;is a 1BHK apartment in&nbsp;Andheri, Mumbai&nbsp;which he formerly used to share with his mother. Most&nbsp;celebs&nbsp;prefer to have costly and comfortable houses so they can flex about it. This contradicts the way Nana&nbsp;Patekar&nbsp;leads his lifestyle in his 1BHK apartment in&nbsp;Andheri, Mumbai. It explains how he leads his lifestyle because his simple home is surely a down-to-earth attribute.&nbsp;Nana Patekar&#8216;s achievements in the entirety of his career and still counting are like a golden feather in his cap as he is a great philanthropist and has great empathy towards the people